00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:22.470
I don't really know
how to put it anymore.

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:28.510
I've done a lot of journalism over
the years, starting around 2007

00:02:28.510 --> 00:02:30.940
in the Middle East and East Africa.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:34.540
And this piece just comes
out of having been --

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:38.010
about a year, two years ago
just before Libya fell apart,

00:02:38.010 --> 00:02:41.760
traveling around with the
militia, all over the country.

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:43.670
And I know you say
the word "militia,"

00:02:43.670 --> 00:02:45.640 position:56%
and everybody goes, "Ohhh, militia."

00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:50.850
You know, but everybody in this
room would be in a militia.

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:52.800
So it's a very, very common thing.

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.400
And when you move through
different parts of Libya,

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:59.180
you move from one militia's command
to another militia's command.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:01.870
And that's just how you circulate.

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:05.360
And so when I was there
I met a young man,

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:11.070
a militia meter [phonetic]
who fought in the revolution

00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:15.650
that overthrew Gaddafi, and
he had been seriously wounded.

00:03:15.650 --> 00:03:20.710
He had a big scar on his
cheek which deformed his face.

00:03:20.710 --> 00:03:26.210
And I was just thinking about
what it would be like to be him.

00:03:26.210 --> 00:03:29.100
And I kept looking at his scar
and thinking it was a certain kind

00:03:29.100 --> 00:03:32.350
of writing on his cheek,
kind of calligraphy.

00:03:32.350 --> 00:03:38.800
So anyway, the poem is in
five parts, like I said.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:49.130
One. Once I cleared the choppers,
wop-wop-wop, the airstrip opened

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:55.830
up into a treeless drift of sand,
where I heard a distant hammer tap

00:03:55.830 --> 00:04:01.240
against the wind and smelled
scorched concrete wafting

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:05.260
from shell holes in the runway.

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:11.030
Then we were speeding along
in the back of an open truck,

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:15.960
its axles shuddering over
hardpan, as I rubbernecked

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:21.910
at burned-out tanks, turrets
blown to the roadside,

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:29.020
seeming somehow sadder
that the men who died.

00:04:29.020 --> 00:04:37.500
Two. Just a boy who played
soccer until the revolution,

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:44.000
he learned with a bad
shoulder how to fire an AK-47,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.250
shoot off of mortar so he didn't
burn his hands, talk away fear.

00:04:52.350 --> 00:04:55.590
The radio broadcasting endless
hero victim chatter sent him racing

00:04:55.590 --> 00:04:56.890
behind a wall, hiding from
the sniper's crosshairs.

00:04:56.890 --> 00:04:58.410
Pinwheeling shrapnel sent them to
the hospital, where he suffered

00:04:58.410 --> 00:04:59.710
as much from boredom as his wound.

00:04:59.710 --> 00:05:01.050
Playing with a lizard he holds by
the tail, the panting ribs pulse

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:02.350
as he dangles it head-down.

00:05:02.350 --> 00:05:03.650
His bandaged cheek crisscrossed
with tape, looking like it aches.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:05.130 position:56%
The hot breeze dries sweat from his
face as the lizard whiplashes loose,

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:06.540
scrambling across the sheet
to disappear under the bed,

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:07.840
one wounded foot leaving
pinpricks of blood.

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:09.510
Not a trail or code, just the tail
left dangling in the boy's fingers,

00:05:09.510 --> 00:05:10.810
as he laughs and, swinging
it around,

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:12.110
shows it to his mother,
frowning, "What's that?"

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:13.410
And snatches it away.

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:17.890
Three. Each time the boy, grown
up now, is forced to flash ID,

00:05:17.890 --> 00:05:22.600
his scar tissues calligraphy
writes on his body the history

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:24.710 position:56%
of his own scalloped, twisted flesh.

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:28.610
Shrugging off my pose
of objectivity.

00:05:28.610 --> 00:05:37.070
Shrinking, puckering, the skin
grafts on his burns shine white

00:05:37.070 --> 00:05:39.420
as phosphorus in the sun.

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:43.070
And whatever I write down,
the counter text scrawled

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:56.250
on his cheek revises itself each
time his mouth flexes into a grin

00:05:56.250 --> 00:06:05.750 position:56%
or frown, as year by year whatever's
written there gets that much harder

00:06:05.750 --> 00:06:13.730
to decipher that much
further from the war.

00:06:15.240 --> 00:06:35.850
Until in the mirror, he'll see
and won't see his own scars.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:34.460
Four. In shade and sunlight, the
lizard grows a new tail that writes

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:39.380
in dust over a broken
cobble, its slithering trail

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:45.840
until it stops short, heart pulsing
in its throat, red eyes fixed

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:51.740
on that foreign shape which
takes out a notebook, scribbles.

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:56.840
Green and brown skin, broken
black diamonds arranged

00:07:56.840 --> 00:08:04.150
in vertical stripes, claws that
look like hands of a fever victim.

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:08.210
And then scribbled
notes and neutral tones

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:11.710
about mortar fire, flak jackets.

00:08:11.710 --> 00:08:16.670
The strap on the helmet that is
always too lose or too tight.

00:08:16.670 --> 00:08:20.770
The boy's bombed house,
shockwaves blowing

00:08:20.770 --> 00:08:25.310
out the windows to let in riot gas.

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:28.050
An adrenaline rush.

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:35.920
The smell of tears, chemical
as ammonia and as harsh.

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:46.740
Five. All around me, the
sound of men sleeping.

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:52.020
Their bodies shifting
slightly in their dreaming.

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:56.470
The engines of the
trucks still cooling,

00:08:56.470 --> 00:09:00.390
giving off little ticks and pings.

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:06.010
And then I was climbing
out of my blankets to slip

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:13.130
under the tent's canopy, stumbling
away from mumbling and snores.

00:09:13.130 --> 00:09:17.860
The desert cold making
the dew-damp sand stiffen

00:09:17.860 --> 00:09:26.110 position:56%
so it crunched underfoot, as I crept
beyond the watchman to take a piss.

00:09:26.110 --> 00:09:30.780
And at the edge of the camp near
the chickens and their coop,

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:36.570
heads tucked under wings
was a fox staring back.

00:09:36.570 --> 00:09:41.070
Or what I thought was a fox,
ducking down into the shadows

00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:44.180
and disappearing behind the trucks

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:49.100 position:56%
that in the morning would obliterate
its precise four-clawed tracks.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:53.930
But the next night and the
next would keep on coming back,

00:09:53.930 --> 00:09:56.370
until the chickens got eaten

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:59.080
or the fox was killed.

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:06.130
Then pattering of my own piss
brought me back into the cold.

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:10.580
The sky overhead, dark and bright.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:16.590
Bundled bodies in the dawn
beginning to levitate.

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:22.230
Whose elbows dreamed
up the chokehold?

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:25.180
Who pushes back the boundaries

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:31.650
so that no man's land is the only
high-bond [phonetic] homeland,

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:34.130
patree [phonetic]?

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:42.030
Who strips us of our shadows so
that our histories turn to glass?

00:10:43.210 --> 00:10:47.060
And then it was time for breakfast.

00:10:47.060 --> 00:10:55.240 position:56%
To sit, pee, smoke and take my place
besides the others in the truck.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:01.870
Then I'll finish with
a short poem from my --

00:11:05.110 --> 00:11:06.660
I don't know what to call her.

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:09.620
You know, she came into
my life via divorce.

00:11:09.620 --> 00:11:16.320
So I'm not really her biological
dad, but I feel like her dad.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:20.820
So we have this little code.

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:26.760
I'm her dear almost dad, and
she's my dear almost daughter.

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:29.590
So we're both each other's dad.

00:11:29.590 --> 00:11:34.580
That works.

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:36.880
Second Sight.

00:11:39.770 --> 00:11:46.330
In my fantasy of fatherhood,
in which I'm your real father,

00:11:46.330 --> 00:11:54.940
not just the almost dad arriving
through random channels of divorce,

00:11:54.940 --> 00:12:00.330
you and I don't lie to one another.

00:12:00.330 --> 00:12:05.230
Shrugging each other off when
words get the best of us,

00:12:05.230 --> 00:12:10.700
but coming full circle
with wan smiles.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:14.440
When you hole up inside
yourself, headphones

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:21.700
and computer screen taking you
away, I want to fill in ten years

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:25.990
that if I'm still alive,
you'll still look at me

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:34.930 position:56%
with that same wary expectancy, your
surreptitious, cool-eyed appraisal,

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:39.650 position:56%
debating if my love for you is real.

00:12:40.980 --> 00:12:45.520
Am I destined to be
those shark-faced waves

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:50.100
that my death will one
day make you enter?

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:57.940
You and your mother make
such a self-sufficient pair.

00:12:57.940 --> 00:13:03.910
In thrift stores, looking for your
prom dress, what father could stand

00:13:03.910 --> 00:13:07.410
up to your unsparing eyes,

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:14.500 position:56%
gauging with such erotic calculation
your figure in the mirror?

00:13:15.550 --> 00:13:21.180
Back of it all, when I
indulge my second sight,

00:13:21.180 --> 00:13:25.760
all I see are dead zones.

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:34.030
No grandchildren, no evenings at
the beach, no bonfires in a future

00:13:34.030 --> 00:13:39.980
that allows one glass of
wine per shot of insulin.

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:50.260
Where we both agree that I love you
always, no matter my love's flawed,

00:13:50.260 --> 00:14:01.320
aging partiality, my occupation
now is to help you be alone.

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:03.120
Thank you.

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:12.190
